@flexiarg t3/expectation-scaffold
@title Confident Adaptation
@sigils [🧭/规]
@audience programme-leads, trainers, policy-owners
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/intervention-triad
@see t3/adaptive-delivery-spine, t3/living-materials-stewardship
@next t3/adaptive-delivery-spine
@tier intervention
@confidence high
@npt-domain 1.2 Communal Specification
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Trainers can adapt confidently because they know what is fixed and what is flexible. Where this clarity is absent, delivery fragments and trainers cannot coordinate their actions or assess whether they are doing enough.

  + context: National T3 programmes attract diverse participants with uneven prior knowledge and shifting institutional mandates; ambiguity about what is required versus optional undermines delivery.
  + if: You want trainers to act confidently and consistently while still adapting locally.
  + however: Vague participation rules and undefined completion criteria leave trainers unsure what they can legitimately promise, and delivery fragments across institutions.
  + then: Publish a minimal expectation scaffold: required sessions, optional pathways, and a stated "ready-to-deliver" threshold. Provide a short, plain-language briefing on what T3 is and is not, plus a self-check checklist for trainers.
  + because: Clarity lowers cognitive load, reduces mismatch between expectations and capacity, and improves coordination across distributed trainers.
      + mechanism: Clear requirements reduce ambiguity, which increases trainer confidence and yields more consistent delivery choices.
      + counterfactual: If we only add more content or sessions without clarifying requirements, confusion persists and delivery remains fragmented.
      + applies-when: Multiple cohorts, diverse mandates, and distributed delivery teams need shared expectations.
      + does-not-apply: A single local team with an agreed curriculum and direct supervision already has alignment.
      + signals: Repeated questions about "what counts" or inconsistent module selection across trainers.
      + evidence: "It wasn't very clear to us how many sessions we needed to have attended, which ones were fundamental" (T2A); "I didn't realise when I first signed up for it that these courses were part of this research project" (T2B); "It was useful to have a template of what was expected" (T3). COM-B: "I understand what this requires of me" M=4.90.
  + next-steps:
      - Create a one-page "T3 in Brief" with required/optional components.
      - Define a minimal competency checklist with examples of acceptable adaptations.
      - Add an onboarding call focused on expectations and scope.
  + governance:
      - practice: review and update the scaffold annually with trainer input.
      - metric: trainers report clarity on requirements before first delivery.
